someone can’t manage their own affairs because they’re mentally incapable or severely disabled, you can apply for the right to deal with their benefits on their behalf.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Only one appointee can act on behalf of someone who is entitled to benefits given out by the Department for Work and Pensions (<abbr title=\"Department for Work and Pensions\">DWP</abbr>). </p>\n\n<p>An appointee can be:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>an individual, eg a friend or relative </li>\n  <li>an organisation or representative of an organisation, eg a solicitor or local council</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Your responsibilities as an appointee</h2>\n\n<p>As an appointee you take full responsibility for making and maintaining any benefit claims. You must also manage the way the benefit is spent. </p>\n\n<p>This means you must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>sign the claim form instead of the person claiming benefits</li>\n  <li>tell the benefit office of any changes which can affect the amount of benefit the claimant gets</li>\n  <li>claim any benefits the person is entitled to</li>\n  <li>spend the benefit - which is paid direct to you - in the best interests of the claimant</li>\n  <li>tell the benefit office if the person claiming benefit becomes capable of managing their own affairs</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If benefit is overpaid then, depending on the circumstances, you could be held responsible.                                         </p>\n\n<h2>How to apply to become an appointee</h2>\n\n<p>Contact the Benefit enquiry line and tell them that someone you know needs your help to either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>claim benefit - because they can’t do it themselves</li>\n  <li>manage their existing benefit - because they can’t do it themselves               </li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Benefit enquiry line</strong></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"&#109;&#097;&#105;&#108;&#116;&#111;:&#066;&#069;&#076;&#045;&#067;&#117;&#115;&#116;&#111;&#109;&#101;&#114;&#045;&#083;&#101;&#114;&#118;&#105;&#099;&#101;&#115;&#064;&#100;&#119;&#112;&#046;&#103;&#115;&#105;&#046;&#103;&#111;&#118;&#046;&#117;&#107;\">&#066;&#069;&#076;&#045;&#067;&#117;&#115;&#116;&#111;&#109;&#101;&#114;&#045;&#083;&#101;&#114;&#118;&#105;&#099;&#101;&#115;&#064;&#100;&#119;&#112;&#046;&#103;&#115;&#105;&#046;&#103;&#111;&#118;&#046;&#117;&#107;</a><br />\n<strong>Freephone:</strong> 0800 882 200<br />\n<strong>Textphone:</strong> 0800 243 355<br />\nMonday to Friday, 8:30am to 6:30pm</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Next steps</h2>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>The <abbr title=\"Department for Work and Pensions\">DWP</abbr> will arrange to visit the claimant to assess if they’re incapable of managing their affairs and that an appointee is needed.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>The <abbr title=\"Department for Work and Pensions\">DWP</abbr> will interview you to make sure that you’re suitable and willing to act as the appointee.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>During the interview, and after the visit to the claimant, an ‘Application for appointment to act on behalf of someone else’ (Form BF56) is completed by you and the interviewer.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>If the <abbr title=\"Department for Work and Pensions\">DWP</abbr> agrees that the claimant needs help and that you’re suitable you’ll be formally appointed to act on their behalf. If this hasn’t happened, you aren’t yet an ‘appointee’.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h2>Reviewing appointees</h2>\n\n<p>Once you&rsquo;re authorised as an appointee the <abbr title=\"Department for Work and Pensions\">DWP</abbr> will continue to monitor the situation to make sure it&rsquo;s still the most suitable arrangement for you and the person you&rsquo;re an appointee for.</p>\n\n<h2>Cancelling the right to be an appointee</h2>\n\n<p>Your appointment can be revoked (withdrawn) if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you don&rsquo;t act properly under the terms of the appointment</li>\n  <li>the claimant is clearly able to manage their own benefits</li>\n  <li>you become incapable yourself</li>\n  <li>you don&rsquo;t want to continue as an appointee </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>To cancel your role as an appointee you must give 4 weeks&rsquo; written notice to the benefit office.</p>\n\n<h2>Further information</h2>\n\n<p>Full details of the appointment process can be found in the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.dwp.gov.uk/publications/specialist-guides/agents-appointees-attorneys\" title=\"Agents, appointees, attorneys and deputies guide\">&lsquo;Agents, appointees, attorneys and deputies guide&rsquo;.</a></p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>There’s more information about help and finances for the disabled in <a href=\"/financial-help-disabled\" title=\"Financial help if you're disabled\">Financial help if you’re disabled</a> and <a href=\"/apply-needs-assessment-social-services\" title=\"Apply for a needs assessment\">Apply for a needs assessment</a>.</p>\n</div>\n\n","alternative_title":"Becoming an appointee for social security benefits"},"updated_at":"2012-11-12T13:03:30+00:00","tags":[{"title":"Lasting Power of Attorney, being in care and your financial affairs","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/births-deaths-marriages%2Flasting-power-attorney.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes dealing with benefits, taxes and leaving care","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=births-deaths-marriages%2Flasting-power-attorney","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/births-deaths-marriages/lasting-power-attorney"},"parent":{"title":"Births, deaths, marriages and care","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/births-deaths-marriages.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes civil partnerships, splitting up and Lasting Power of Attorney","short_description":"","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=births-deaths-marriages","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/births-deaths-marriages"},"parent":null}},{"title":"Carers and disability benefits","id":"h